00:46:46.480 --> 00:46:50.170
about forms and administrators
for later maybe.

00:46:50.170 --> 00:46:51.740
But I'm more curious--

00:46:51.740 --> 00:46:53.410
or maybe I'll start
with the preface

00:46:53.410 --> 00:46:55.750
that we're a part of
a technology company.

00:46:55.750 --> 00:46:57.310
And it certainly
feels like the world

00:46:57.310 --> 00:46:59.750
is moving faster and faster.

00:46:59.750 --> 00:47:03.040
And we want to, whether it's
multitasking or enabling

00:47:03.040 --> 00:47:05.470
people to move faster,
you put a lot of the onus

00:47:05.470 --> 00:47:07.990
on the medical
system and doctors

00:47:07.990 --> 00:47:09.880
to slow the system
down, it seems like,

00:47:09.880 --> 00:47:12.010
to not treat the
body like a machine.

00:47:12.010 --> 00:47:16.810
Yet, what are your thoughts
from a patient's perspective?

00:47:16.810 --> 00:47:19.600
The ability to take
some ibuprofens

00:47:19.600 --> 00:47:23.050
when I have a headache
and solve the problem is--

00:47:23.050 --> 00:47:25.270
that's nice to hand that
off to the doctor and say,

00:47:25.270 --> 00:47:26.890
why are you prescribing
me ibuprofens?

00:47:26.890 --> 00:47:29.020
But I can get this
off the shelf.

00:47:29.020 --> 00:47:31.900
How do patients approach
medicine differently

00:47:31.900 --> 00:47:35.220
and slow things down, and
look for longer solutions,

00:47:35.220 --> 00:47:36.160
moralistic solutions?

00:47:36.160 --> 00:47:38.350
VICTORIA SWEET: That's a
really thoughtful question.

00:47:38.350 --> 00:47:41.170
Thank you.

00:47:41.170 --> 00:47:43.780
Well, what I would say is this.

00:47:43.780 --> 00:47:47.552
I think there's actually
two flavors of patients,

00:47:47.552 --> 00:47:48.760
two flavors of people really.

00:47:48.760 --> 00:47:51.410
Some people really
like medications.

00:47:51.410 --> 00:47:52.235
They like meds.

00:47:52.235 --> 00:47:52.860
They like labs.

00:47:52.860 --> 00:47:53.830
They like going to the doctor.

00:47:53.830 --> 00:47:55.079
They like-- they just like it.

00:47:55.079 --> 00:47:56.260
They like meds.

00:47:56.260 --> 00:47:57.760
And then there's a
whole other group

00:47:57.760 --> 00:47:59.680
that don't like meds, of which
I happen to belong to them.

00:47:59.680 --> 00:48:02.320
And what usually happens
with docs in an open system,

00:48:02.320 --> 00:48:05.320
is the docs that like to
prescribe meds and just

00:48:05.320 --> 00:48:07.780
naturally practice this
way, collect patients

00:48:07.780 --> 00:48:09.510
who like to have medications.

00:48:09.510 --> 00:48:12.620
There's a whole lot of
people who believe in meds.

00:48:12.620 --> 00:48:15.580
But I'm not one of them, either
as a doctor or as a patient.

00:48:15.580 --> 00:48:18.820
And I would tend to collect
patients who think like me.

00:48:18.820 --> 00:48:22.250
So I don't think it's
just one or the other.

00:48:22.250 --> 00:48:27.400
I think for the people who
are reluctant to take meds,

00:48:27.400 --> 00:48:29.870
they don't usually
take meds very much.

00:48:29.870 --> 00:48:32.170
And if they can get away
with just taking something

00:48:32.170 --> 00:48:34.870
off the shelf, sort of why not?

00:48:34.870 --> 00:48:39.380
So I think that's how I
would answer that question.

00:48:39.380 --> 00:48:42.920
I'm not sure if I got
to the nubbin of it.

00:48:42.920 --> 00:48:45.870
Because you started out by
talking about everything

00:48:45.870 --> 00:48:49.170
moving faster and faster.

00:48:49.170 --> 00:48:52.275
And that as a patient, how can
you get things to slow down?

00:48:52.275 --> 00:48:54.400
And in a way, I don't even
think it's as a patient.

00:48:54.400 --> 00:48:55.520
It's as a person.

00:48:55.520 --> 00:48:56.490
I mean I think--

00:48:56.490 --> 00:48:58.656
so this is, again,
maybe a little off

00:48:58.656 --> 00:48:59.530
for me talking about.

00:49:03.090 --> 00:49:04.980
I think as far as
our health goes,

00:49:04.980 --> 00:49:07.620
we couldn't live
in a society that

00:49:07.620 --> 00:49:12.660
was more difficult to
be sane, and centered,

00:49:12.660 --> 00:49:16.460
and enjoy your life than the
society you live in right now.

00:49:16.460 --> 00:49:18.800
And I think-- you
know, "sane" actually

00:49:18.800 --> 00:49:22.220
is from "sanus," which
means "healthy" in Latin.

00:49:22.220 --> 00:49:26.570
And "health," which
is "solus," actually

00:49:26.570 --> 00:49:27.980
is connected to salvation.

00:49:30.630 --> 00:49:34.110
Then I like the one that's
"hello," which actually means

00:49:34.110 --> 00:49:35.910
"health to you."

00:49:35.910 --> 00:49:37.800
Because in old English,
"hal" was health.

00:49:37.800 --> 00:49:41.440
And they're all related
to this idea of wholeness.

00:49:41.440 --> 00:49:45.450
So whole, and hal, and
health, and wealth--

00:49:45.450 --> 00:49:46.020
I think.

00:49:46.020 --> 00:49:46.740
I haven't looked that up yet.

00:49:46.740 --> 00:49:48.739
But I decided the other
day, I think wealth fits

00:49:48.739 --> 00:49:51.590
into this wholeness model.

00:49:51.590 --> 00:49:52.930
We're fragmented.

00:49:52.930 --> 00:49:56.010
Our attention is fragmented.

00:49:56.010 --> 00:49:59.050
We're just in this kind of
piecemeal, sort of state.

00:49:59.050 --> 00:50:01.025
And I think it's not
a good state to be in.

00:50:04.280 --> 00:50:05.632
REBECCA MOORE: Another question.

00:50:05.632 --> 00:50:08.500
AUDIENCE: Building on Salim's
thing, I think he says--

00:50:08.500 --> 00:50:10.685
I think it's separating
symptom from the source.

00:50:10.685 --> 00:50:13.060
So if you have a headache,
and that's a symptom, you say,

00:50:13.060 --> 00:50:13.960
I can take an Advil.

00:50:13.960 --> 00:50:15.390
And that will go away.

00:50:15.390 --> 00:50:17.480
And you can just keep
doing that for a while.

00:50:17.480 --> 00:50:19.520
But you're not addressing
the root cause.

00:50:19.520 --> 00:50:22.350
So if I can treat a symptom,
I will deal with it myself.

00:50:22.350 --> 00:50:24.610
But if I can't get
past that, then that's

00:50:24.610 --> 00:50:26.620
where I go to the doctor,
to help me figure out

00:50:26.620 --> 00:50:28.408
what's actually going on.

00:50:28.408 --> 00:50:29.830
VICTORIA SWEET: Correct answer.

00:50:29.830 --> 00:50:30.450
Thank you.

00:50:30.450 --> 00:50:31.840
AUDIENCE: Well, you're
supposed to comment on that.

00:50:31.840 --> 00:50:32.631
VICTORIA SWEET: Oh.

00:50:32.631 --> 00:50:33.970
[LAUGHTER]

00:50:33.970 --> 00:50:35.120
I totally agree with it.

00:50:35.120 --> 00:50:36.600
It's exactly right.

00:50:36.600 --> 00:50:37.410
That's exactly it.

00:50:37.410 --> 00:50:41.460
Is, if you can make it go away
on your own, and that's-- then,

00:50:41.460 --> 00:50:43.287
I don't have a problem
with that actually.

00:50:43.287 --> 00:50:44.620
I think that's a good way to go.

00:50:44.620 --> 00:50:45.780
AUDIENCE: That's your
measure of efficiency though.

00:50:45.780 --> 00:50:47.792
Are you looking at
[INAUDIBLE] efficiencies?

00:50:47.792 --> 00:50:48.750
I had a headache today.

00:50:48.750 --> 00:50:49.380
I took a pill.

00:50:49.380 --> 00:50:51.170
It went away.

00:50:51.170 --> 00:50:52.860
It looks like it's
extremely efficient.

00:50:52.860 --> 00:50:55.075
But if every single day
I'm taking this pill,

00:50:55.075 --> 00:50:57.450
and I'm constantly dealing
with that, over the long term,

00:50:57.450 --> 00:50:59.150
that's extremely inefficient.

00:50:59.150 --> 00:51:00.660
And if I treat the
source of that,

00:51:00.660 --> 00:51:02.400
it takes me longer
to treat the source,

00:51:02.400 --> 00:51:04.500
but it solves it for a
much longer duration.

00:51:04.500 --> 00:51:07.414
And therefore, it's much more
efficient in the long run.

00:51:07.414 --> 00:51:08.580
VICTORIA SWEET: Good answer.

00:51:08.580 --> 00:51:09.460
It is.

00:51:09.460 --> 00:51:10.150
It's super.

00:51:10.150 --> 00:51:10.400
Thank you.

00:51:10.400 --> 00:51:11.816
AUDIENCE: To get
to Salim's point,

00:51:11.816 --> 00:51:17.270
I think it's very hard for a
certain segment of patients

00:51:17.270 --> 00:51:18.410
to get over that.

00:51:18.410 --> 00:51:20.030
They want the quick fix.

00:51:20.030 --> 00:51:22.400
So, in some ways,
many physicians

00:51:22.400 --> 00:51:25.100
respond to that by prescribing.

00:51:25.100 --> 00:51:27.770
I think many-- and I speak
as a physician myself.

00:51:27.770 --> 00:51:30.830
Many of us would like to sit
down, talk to our patients,

00:51:30.830 --> 00:51:32.055
spend time.

00:51:32.055 --> 00:51:33.680
And sometimes patients,
like me, doc, I

00:51:33.680 --> 00:51:34.765
don't have time for this.

00:51:34.765 --> 00:51:36.390
I'm not going invest
in my health care.

00:51:36.390 --> 00:51:38.120
I just want-- give
me the antidepressant

00:51:38.120 --> 00:51:38.780
and I'll feel better.

00:51:38.780 --> 00:51:40.140
And I'll have time
for therapy later.

00:51:40.140 --> 00:51:41.848
But I don't have time
for that right now.

00:51:41.848 --> 00:51:43.700
So there's this
whole sea change,

00:51:43.700 --> 00:51:47.600
that has to also start from the
patient point of view, actually

00:51:47.600 --> 00:51:49.792
wanting to invest
time in themselves.

00:51:49.792 --> 00:51:52.000
AUDIENCE: And if you have
to see a thousand patients,

00:51:52.000 --> 00:51:53.480
you don't have time to do that.

00:51:53.480 --> 00:51:55.010
VICTORIA SWEET: Correct.

00:51:55.010 --> 00:51:57.770
REBECCA MOORE: Anyone else?

00:51:57.770 --> 00:52:00.410
So I one last question, maybe.

00:52:00.410 --> 00:52:02.630
Do you feel that
you, as a clinician,

00:52:02.630 --> 00:52:04.400
that you are alone in this?

00:52:04.400 --> 00:52:06.590
Or, as you go around
and you're talking

00:52:06.590 --> 00:52:10.040
with other doctors, and nurses,
and so on, around the country,

00:52:10.040 --> 00:52:14.785
is this message of slow
medicine resonating?

00:52:14.785 --> 00:52:15.660
VICTORIA SWEET: Yeah.

00:52:15.660 --> 00:52:16.620
It sure is.

00:52:16.620 --> 00:52:20.100
And I sometimes wish I was
a lot more of a general,

00:52:20.100 --> 00:52:22.290
rather than a philosopher.

00:52:22.290 --> 00:52:26.220
Because there's a whole movement
that is brewing out there.

00:52:26.220 --> 00:52:31.160
There's so much frustration
among doctors, and nurses

00:52:31.160 --> 00:52:32.180
especially.

00:52:32.180 --> 00:52:34.650
I mean as much
nurses, as doctors.

00:52:34.650 --> 00:52:37.750
That, we're just stuck
in front of the computer.

00:52:37.750 --> 00:52:40.320
It's just maddening.

00:52:40.320 --> 00:52:41.970
So there's a huge--

00:52:41.970 --> 00:52:43.920
I've spoken to, like,
thousands of people

00:52:43.920 --> 00:52:46.530
by now, personally, in
all these different talks.

00:52:46.530 --> 00:52:48.300
And everybody wants
something done

00:52:48.300 --> 00:52:49.140
about it, which is
one of the things I've

00:52:49.140 --> 00:52:51.270
thought about electronic
health records and getting--

00:52:51.270 --> 00:52:53.436
because that would at least
get us off the computer.

00:52:53.436 --> 00:52:55.660
It's not complicated.

00:52:55.660 --> 00:52:58.260
I don't think it's as
complicated a solution as it

00:52:58.260 --> 00:53:01.435
looks like at first, if we
can just get back the time.

00:53:04.010 --> 00:53:04.760
REBECCA MOORE: OK.

00:53:04.760 --> 00:53:08.390
We'll have [INAUDIBLE]

00:53:08.390 --> 00:53:10.310
AUDIENCE: Since
we're at Google, I'd

00:53:10.310 --> 00:53:14.270
be curious about your comment
on the use of Google Glass

00:53:14.270 --> 00:53:16.130
in the doctor/patient setting.

00:53:16.130 --> 00:53:18.710
So a clinic, that
I will not name,

00:53:18.710 --> 00:53:20.710
has now gone to
using Google Glasses.

00:53:20.710 --> 00:53:23.030
So you walk into the
clinic, the room.

00:53:23.030 --> 00:53:25.430
Your doctor has a
Google Glass on.

00:53:25.430 --> 00:53:27.470
And on the other side
of the Google Glass

00:53:27.470 --> 00:53:31.210
is a transcriptionist, probably
in India somewhere, outsourced,

00:53:31.210 --> 00:53:33.560
that is documenting
every single word

00:53:33.560 --> 00:53:35.630
that occurs between
